                <head>357. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On October 25, Admiral <persName corresp="#p_HAJLJ1">Holloway</persName> reported
                    to the Chief of Naval Operations that all United States military forces had been
                    withdrawn from Lebanon, and that the operation was “completed”. (<gloss
                        target="#t_CINCSPECOMME1">CINCSPECOMME</gloss> telegram 251221Z; National
                    Archives and Records Administration, RG 218, <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>
                    Files) The Army Attaché in Lebanon reported that the departure of the last of
                    the U.S. troops passed quietly and without incident. He noted that the “country
                    continues calm with Beirut again a thriving commercial center.” (<gloss
                        target="#t_USARMA1">USARMA</gloss> telegram CX 357, October 28; <hi
                        rend="italic">ibid.</hi>) The withdrawal of British troops from Jordan began
                    on October 20, and the airlift of the main body of paratroopers from Amman began
                    on October 25. (Telegram 1183 from Amman, October 24; Department of State,
                    Central Files, 785.00/10–2458) The <gloss target="#t_CINCSPECOMME1"
                        >CINCSPECOMME</gloss> telegram is included in <ref
                        target="frus1958-60v11mSupp">the microfiche supplement</ref>.</p>
            </div>
